text=>>comment%3c%3c%0a(:title Buddhism Connect - How thinking can make pain worse:)%0aSummary:Email teaching from Lama Shenpen on the nature of pain%0aSource:Buddhism Connect: Email Teachings http://buddhismconnect.c.topica.com/maapI7vab8ZrubriOFWeaeQC5S/%0aCategories:[[!Articles]],[[!Humanism]]%0aTags: pain, buddhism%0a(:tags-hide pain, buddhism:)%0aParent:SavedArticles(.HomePage)%0aIncludeMe:[[SavedArticles.HomePage]]%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a(:source lang=email -getcode:)%0aFrom: Buddhism Connect %3cbuddhismconnect@app.topica.com>%0aSubject: How thinking can make pain worse%0aDate: Sat, 09 Jun 2012 00:15:00 -0700%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0a!!How thinking can make pain worse%0a%0a:Summary:Pain is the nature of Samsara and it will be with us for the whole of the path. We can however learn not to make it worse by adding to it the suffering caused by negative thinking, such as ''{$LQuote}I can't stand this{$RQuote}''. Thoughts like this are unnecessary and we can let them go.%0a%0a!!!A student asks:%0a%0aI experience a great deal of physical pain and struggle to understand%0awhy. I can only come up with the fact that everyone suffers. Some people%0atalk as if I could be rid of my pain if only I could get my mind set%0aright, which doesn't help me. I try to stay in the moment and enjoy each%0amoment, but would be grateful for some advice.%0a%0a!!!Lama Shenpen replies:%0a%0aAs far as making sense of the pain is concerned I think the only thing%0ato think is that pain is the nature of samsara. It is the first Noble%0aTruth the Buddha taught because he was not out to deceive us. He%0aelevated it to a Noble Truth because until we truly understand the depth%0aand true nature of suffering there is no final Liberation from it. It is%0agoing to be with us for the whole of the path whether we want it or not.%0a%0aWe all have to suffer and we none of us know when we will have to bear%0awhat and for how long. Our situation can change so drastically and so%0asuddenly and some forms of suffering go on and on. When we contemplate%0ahow this is true for every being there is everywhere we start to yearn%0afor what goes beyond samsara &mdash; a state of mind in which we can face any%0asituation however intense with equanimity. This is the highest spiritual%0aaccomplishment, its called Enlightenment. We can keep aspiring for it%0aand for the conditions that will bring it about for ourselves and all%0abeings. Such an aspiration is not just wishful thinking. Such aspiration%0ais the path itself. The constant aspiration is the path.%0a%0aEnlightenment itself is not conditioned but we are. We are so easily%0adistracted and discouraged from even aspiring to realise what lies%0abeyond all suffering. But the pain doesn't go away. Even if it goes%0atemporarily there is no guarantee that it won't come back until we are%0aEnlightened. That is when we realise the true nature of reality which is%0aour own being. It is a long path and we have to suffer a lot on the way.%0a%0aIf you can relate to your present suffering with some kind of sense of%0ait being your path, then the suffering itself becomes your practice.%0aJust being able to let go of negative thinking and struggling with the%0apain and being more simple about it, that already means you are making%0athe suffering into the path. Gradually as you learn to not add to your%0asuffering by negative thinking, you will find the pain itself has a kind%0aof quality of awareness to it that can sometimes feel strangely ok...%0aand that it is the thinking of ''{$LQuote}I cannot stand this{$RQuote}'' that is the real%0asuffering &mdash; the struggle... the remembering how long it has gone on and%0adreading how long it might last... this is thinking and adding something%0aheavy and stressful to the original sensation of pain. This can be%0areduced by noticing it is not the pain itself but an added suffering. It%0ais possible to notice it is thinking and has no more status than any%0aother thought. Such thinking can be reduced tremendously by simply not%0afeeding it with the belief that it is necessary. Such thinking is not%0anecessary... it is just like any other thought that you let go of all%0athe time. It is possible to let it go.%0a%0aThat is a huge thing to learn. It is massive. But even to learn it a%0atiny bit brings relief. So that is all I can suggest really. Pain such%0aas yours is a harsh teacher but in the end may be kind. The rest of us%0aare relatively heedless because we are not suffering that much right%0anow. You have a goad forcing you to search deeply and to long for%0aEnlightenment with a fierce intensity &mdash; if you can extend this to all%0aother beings who are suffering with you... and we all will be sooner or%0alater... then you are turning your suffering into your spiritual path.%0aIt is not meaningless.%0a%0aI don't know if this helps. I hope it does.%0a%0a----%0a%0aThe Four Noble Truths: The basic teaching of the Buddha:%0a# suffering,%0a# the causes of suffering,%0a# cessation of suffering,%0a# the path out of suffering%0a%0a:Samsara:The endless wandering round in an endless succession of lives each characterised by suffering. It is existence as experienced by unenlightened beings, whether it’s the tread-mill of living from day to day, going nowhere except into old age and death, or the suffering of being trapped in delusion from one life to the next.%0a%0aDiscover the Heart of Buddhism: sign up for Lama Shenpen's Distance%0aLearning Course http://buddhismconnect.c.topica.com/maapI7vab8ZrBbriOFWeaeQC5S/%0a%0aIf you value these regular email teachings and would like to make a%0adonation to help us keep this service going, then visit our website.%0aBuddhism Connect emails are sent out by the Shrimala Trust, a registered%0acharity (UK no. 1078783), supporting the activity of the Awakened Heart%0aSangha. All subscriber information is kept confidential and never sold.%0a%0aMake a Donation: http://buddhismconnect.c.topica.com/maapI7vab8ZrwbriOFWeaeQC5S/%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a
