3c what and for how long. Our situation can change so drastically and so%0a%3c suddenly and some forms of suffering go on and on. When we contemplate%0a%3c how this is true for every being there is everywhere we start to yearn%0a%3c for what goes beyond samsara &mdash; a state of mind in which we can face any%0a%3c situation however intense with equanimity. This is the highest spiritual%0a%3c accomplishment, its called Enlightenment. We can keep aspiring for it%0a%3c and for the conditions that will bring it about for ourselves and all%0a%3c beings. Such an aspiration is not just wishful thinking. Such aspiration%0a%3c is the path itself. The constant aspiration is the path.%0a%3c %0a%3c Enlightenment itself is not conditioned but we are. We are so easily%0a%3c distracted and discouraged from even aspiring to realise what lies%0a%3c beyond all suffering. But the pain doesn't go away. Even if it goes%0a%3c temporarily there is no guarantee that it won't come back until we are%0a%3c Enlightened. That is when we realise the true nature of reality which is%0a%3c our own being. It is a long path and we have to suffer a lot on the way.%0a%3c %0a%3c If you can relate to your present suffering with some kind of sense of%0a%3c it being your path, then the suffering itself becomes your practice.%0a%3c Just being able to let go of negative thinking and struggling with the%0a%3c pain and being more simple about it, that already means you are making%0a%3c the suffering into the path. Gradually as you learn to not add to your%0a%3c suffering by negative thinking, you will find the pain itself has a kind%0a%3c of quality of awareness to it that can sometimes feel strangely ok...%0a%3c and that it is the thinking of ''{$LQuote}I cannot stand this{$RQuote}'' that is the real%0a%3c suffering &mdash; the struggle... the remembering how long it has gone on and%0a%3c dreading how long it might last... this is thinking and adding something%0a%3c heavy and stressful to the original sensation of pain. This can be%0a%3c reduced by noticing it is not the pain itself but an added suffering. It%0a%3c is possible to notice it is thinking and has no more status than any%0a%3c other thought. Such thinking can be reduced tremendously by simply not%0a%3c feeding it with the belief that it is necessary. Such thinking is not%0a%3c necessary... it is just like any other thought that you let go of all%0a%3c the time. It is possible to let it go.%0a%3c %0a%3c That is a huge thing to learn. It is massive. But even to learn it a%0a%3c tiny bit brings relief. So that is all I can suggest really. Pain such%0a%3c as yours is a harsh teacher but in the end may be kind. The rest of us%0a%3c are relatively heedless because we are not suffering that much right%0a%3c now. You have a goad forcing you to search deeply and to long for%0a%3c Enlightenment with a fierce intensity &mdash; if you can extend this to all%0a%3c other beings who are suffering with you... and we all will be sooner or%0a%3c later... then you are turning your suffering into your spiritual path.%0a%3c It is not meaningless.%0a%3c %0a%3c I don't know if this helps. I hope it does.%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c The Four Noble Truths: The basic teaching of the Buddha:%0a%3c # suffering,%0a%3c # the causes of suffering,%0a%3c # cessation of suffering,%0a%3c # the path out of suffering%0a%3c %0a%3c :Samsara:The endless wandering round in an endless succession of lives each characterised by suffering. It is existence as experienced by unenlightened beings, whether it’s the tread-mill of living from day to day, going nowhere except into old age and death, or the suffering of being trapped in delusion from one life to the next.%0a%3c %0a%3c Discover the Heart of Buddhism: sign up for Lama Shenpen's Distance%0a%3c Learning Course http://buddhismconnect.c.topica.com/maapI7vab8ZrBbriOFWeaeQC5S/%0a%3c %0a%3c If you value these regular email teachings and would like to make a%0a%3c donation to help us keep this servi